      passage: `Why is it that ocelots purr while jaguars roar? Researchers suspect the answer lies partly in a U-shaped throat bone known as the hyoid. In the ocelot, a much smaller cat than the jaguar, the hyoid is rigid and rumbles as the larynx vibrates, producing a purr. The jaguar&rsquo;s hyoid, by contrast, is somewhat flexible and is joined to the skull by a stretchy ligament the ocelot has no equivalent for. Such features let jaguars and most other big cats loose their powerful roars&mdash;and those same features may well be the very reason that most big cats, unlike the ocelot, cannot purr at all.`,
